About 60% of an adult’s body is made up of H2O. Could that explain why the ocean has always had a natural pull on @erubes1? @erubes1 believes we tend to gravitate towards people, places, and things that bring us comfort. Time spent gazing into the endless horizon has often been associated with clearing one’s mind. Think about it...Alone, perched above the ocean at sunrise, where do your thoughts drift off to? It’s the moments like these that mean everything to @erubes1. No one around, just the peace of the tide as it flows in and out of the lagoon. There’s something about the fresh ocean air that’s therapeutic for @erubes1. The rolling of the waves creates a soothing consistency to sleep to. It’s hard to describe but there’s so much more to the ocean than sand and waves.
—
📍#borabora #frenchpolynesia

Experience a quarter year of Africa with @paul_hanninen. The penguins at the end of this series were astounded after hearing what Paul and his woman had witnessed in Namibia through the past three months. A mountainous bull elephant nearly smashed their rental pick-up, they got away and found themselves in the starlit desert with no civilization in the radius of 60km...with their car stuck in sand! Surrounded by the highest dunes in the world the Sun eventually got up to illuminate the morning in Sossusvlei, and our travelers got helped out. The next thing they remember encountering was a ravenous leopard sizing them up with its piercing gaze, so they thought it's best to find a refuge high enough and fast! — a 35m long rock finger will do just fine. And finally, through the mountains, and uncounted sunrises, our duet found their way to the penguin beach of Cape Town, South Africa, after acquiring some calmness in the Cape of Good Hope. Have you ever been to Africa? How was it for you? If not, tell us what you'd like to see there the most!
—
